title: 'Postmortem agent (kimi_coding/kimi-for-code) rejects temperature: only 1 allowed'
---
## Summary

Postmortem agent is configured with provider=kimi_coding, model=kimi-for-code.
That model rejects any temperature value other than 1 with:

  HTTP 400 \"invalid temperature: only 1 is allowed for this model\"

clawq passes the global default_temperature (0.7) into the request, causing
the postmortem turn to fail on every retry (Attempt 1/3, 2/3, 3/3), spamming
WARN and ERROR lines.

Excerpts from ~/.clawq/daemon.log:
```
[23:54:54.994] [__postmortem_teams:...] -> LLM provider=kimi_coding model=kimi-for-code msgs=3
[23:54:55.986] WARN  Attempt 1/3 failed (HTTP 400 invalid temperature: only 1 is allowed)
[23:54:57.936] WARN  Attempt 2/3 failed (same)
[23:55:01.205] WARN  postmortem agent error for session ... (same)
```

8 occurrences total in current rotation (Telegram-poll-cancel-ERROR also
amplifies log noise but is a separate issue).

Same class of issue covers OpenAI reasoning models (o1/o3 family) which
also require temperature=1.

## Suggested fix

In `src/provider_*.ml`, suppress the `temperature` body field when the
target model is in a known temperature-locked list. Alternatively, parse the
'only 1 is allowed' error string and auto-retry with temperature=1 once.
Cleanest: a provider-side `supports_temperature` capability per model in
`src/models_catalog.ml` (or wherever provider/model metadata lives) and have
each provider's `complete`/`complete_streaming` honor it.

## Related

- B338 postmortem model is using wrong provider — partially overlapping;
  this is a separate symptom (temperature rejection, not provider mismatch).
- B395 postmortem circuit breaker (already done) suppresses additional
  postmortem launches after retries fail, but the per-attempt error storm
  still hits the log.

## Test

Add an `Quick` unit test that builds the request body for a temperature-
locked model and asserts `temperature` is omitted. Add a regression
test that the postmortem agent does not retry on this specific error.